"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782800","Department of Health","false","2017-11-07","<p>All clinically necessary dental treatment is available on the National Health Service. Where cosmetic treatment is deemed clinically necessary, it will be available. Cosmetic dental treatment that is not clinically necessary is not available and there are no plans to make it so.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-11-07T12:01:14.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782800/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782800/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-02","Dental Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to make cosmetic dental treatment more available on the NHS.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","111156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782801","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>The 2016 Adult Improving Access to Psychological Therapies Workforce Census Report is currently being verified and analysed by Health Education England. It will be published as soon this has been completed.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-11-08T17:43:45.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782801/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782801/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-02","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he plans to publish the 2016 Adult Improving Access to Psychological Therapies Workforce Census Report.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","111236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782802","Home Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>We are considering the options for our future immigration very carefully and will outline our proposals in due course.</p><p>The Prime Minister was clear in her speech on 22 September of the need for an implementation period to ensure that people and businesses – both in the UK and in the EU – have time to adjust to the new arrangements in a smooth and orderly way. During the implementation period, people will continue to be able to come and live and work in the UK; but there will be a registration system – an essential preparation for the new regime.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","111179","2017-11-09T16:46:38.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782802/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782802/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782802/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Migrant Workers: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the earliest date on which her Department would have the capacity to include EU-EEA nationals who wish to work in the UK within a visa and work permit system.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","111180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782803","Home Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Government’s top priority is the safety and security of the public. The 2015 Spending Review settlement protected counter-terrorism policing spend until 2020-21 and included a significant capital increase to deliver growth of key counter-terrorist policing capabilities.The Government is in regular dialogue with the police to ensure that the right powers, capabilities and resources are in place across all areas of policing.</p><p>In recognition of the pressures on policing following this year’s terrorist attacks, the Home Secretary has announced a further £24 million for counter-terrorism policing. Work is currently under way to review the UK’s counter-terrorism strategy, CONTEST,including drawing on the lessons learned from the attacks in London and Manchester.</p><p>We remain committed to increasing cross-government spending on counter-terrorism by 30%, from £11.7 billion to £15.1 billion.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-11-09T14:15:52.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782803/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782803/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782803/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Counter-terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether her Department has made a recent assessment of the adequacy of police spending on counter-terrorism.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","111196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782805","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Prevent Strategy defines our fundamental values as including democracy, the rule of law, individual liberty and mutual respect and tolerance of different faiths and beliefs. It is important to articulate British Values as being core and fundamental to life in Britain. They are not uniquely British, but they are the things we value in Britain.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-11-07T14:56:15.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782805/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782805/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782805/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Counter-terrorism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what definition of British Values is used for the purposes of the Prevent Programme.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","111151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782806","Home Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>No estimate has been made of the number of EU citizens already resident in the UK who do not benefit from EU treaty rights or any other rights to residency.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-09T16:25:43.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782806/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782806/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782806/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Immigration: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of how many EU-EEA citizens currently resident in the UK do not benefit from EU treaty rights or any other rights to residency.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","111175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782807","Home Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>We are considering the options for our future immigration very carefully and will outline our proposals in due course.</p><p>The Prime Minister was clear in her speech on 22 September of the need for an implementation period to ensure that people and businesses – both in the UK and in the EU – have time to adjust to the new arrangements in a smooth and orderly way. During the implementation period, people will continue to be able to come and live and work in the UK; but there will be a registration system – an essential preparation for the new regime.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","111180","2017-11-09T16:46:38.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782807/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782807/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782807/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Migrant Workers: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of her Department's ability to instate a registration scheme for EU-EEA citizens wishing to come to work in the UK after March 2019.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","111179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782808","Home Office","false","2017-11-20","<p>The Home Office has 24 public phone lines in use across its contact centres. All of these numbers are chargeable.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2017-11-20T17:24:31.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782808/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782808/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782808/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Home Office: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many and what proportion of her Department's public phone-lines charge members of the public to call.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","111091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782809","Home Office","false","2017-11-08","<p>Please find attached a link to the published statistics on the take up of voluntary returns over the period requested, including by EU nationals:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/638602/returns1-apr-jun-2017-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/638602/returns1-apr-jun-2017-tables.ods</a></p><p>The Home Office does not hold data on whether individuals were rough sleepers in a reportable format. Such information could not be retrieved except by a manual inspection of every applicable personal record. This is likely to incur costs over the cost threshold.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-08T14:31:16.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782809/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782809/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782809/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Homelessness: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many homeless EU citizens have been offered voluntary assisted return in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","111161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782811","Home Office","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Home Office does not hold the information you have requested in a reportable format. The Government publishes Immigration Statistics which details the number of enforced returns of EU citizens to June 2017.</p><p>This can be found at:<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-april-to-june-2017/how-many-people-are-detained-or-returned#enforced-returns-of-eu-nationals" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-april-to-june-2017/how-many-people-are-detained-or-returned#enforced-returns-of-eu-nationals</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-08T14:27:06.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782811/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782811/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Homelessness: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many homeless EU citizens have been arrested and deported in each (a) month since January and (b) nation of the UK.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","111162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782812","Home Office","false","2017-11-21","<p>I refer the Hon. Member to the answer given to the Hon. Member for Hampstead and Kilburn on 2 December 2016, UIN 55490.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-21T17:27:56.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782812/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782812/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Marriage Certificates: Mothers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to introduce legislation to amend marriage certificates to include mothers' names.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","111261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782813","Home Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>Police training and guidance are the responsibility of the College of Policing, which has recently launched a sexual offences Special Investigator Development Programme, and has updated its Authorised Professional Practice on domestic abuse and rape. The College has also launched a new training programme developed by the voluntary sector called ‘Domestic Abuse Matters’ which focuses on improved evidence gathering and understanding of controlling and coercive behaviour. This training is being rolled out across forces.</p><p> </p><p>Through the Police Transformation Fund, the Home Office has also awarded £1.9 million to the College to pilot a new ‘licence to practise’ which will ensure that only those officers who are qualified to carry out specialist investigations in high risk areas like child protection, are able to do so. And, up to £12.4million has also been awarded for the Digital Policing Programme, including the Digital Evidence Transfer Service. This is designed to allow forces to rapidly transmit the increasing body of digital evidence across the criminal justice system.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-11-06T17:29:34.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782813/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782813/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assistance she has provided to the police to support the deployment of qualified specialist investigators to tackle domestic abuse, sexual offences and online crime.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","111193"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782815","Home Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>Home Office immigration policy operates with a presumption against detention. When people are detained, it is for the minimum time possible, and their dignity and welfare is of the utmost importance.</p><p>As part of its response to Stephen Shaw’s review of the welfare of vulnerable persons in immigration detention, the Government introduced the adults at risk in immigration detention policy, which came into force on 12 September 2016. The policy introduced a case-by-case evidence-based assessment of the appropriateness of detention for any individual who is considered vulnerable, balanced against the immigration control considerations that apply in their case. Having been a victim of sexual or gender based violence (including female genital mutilation) is expressly included as an indicator of risk for the purposes of the policy.</p><p>This means that any such victim will be detained only when the immigration control considerations that apply in their case outweigh the risk factors. The policy is supported by the cross-cutting gatekeeper, which assesses vulnerability and provides challenge to decisions about who enters immigration detention, and scrutinises prospects and speed of removal.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-09T16:31:37.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782815/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782815/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans she has to ensure that survivors of sexual violence are not detained in immigration detention centres.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","111230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782816","Home Office","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Home Office is currently subject to a Judicial Review to introduce an alternative (X) ‘gender’ marking in the British passport for those who do not feel represented by the current ‘M’ (Male) or ‘F’ (Female) markings.</p><p>We are reflecting on the issues brought forward by the Judicial Review, and it would not be appropriate to comment on this issue at present.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-08T14:33:33.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782816/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782816/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Passports: Gender","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her policy to introduce non-gender X passports in the UK for people who do not identify with a particular gender.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","111173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782817","Home Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>Following the referendum in June 2016, the Home Office continues to make rigorous preparations for a range of possible outcomes from the UK's negotiations with the EU, as set out in the Home Secretary’s evidence to the Home Affairs Select Committee on 17 October. <a href="http://data.parliament.uk/writtenevidence/committeeevidence.svc/evidencedocument/home-affairs-committee/the-work-of-the-home-secretary/oral/71645.html" target="_blank">http://data.parliament.uk/writtenevidence/committeeevidence.svc/evidencedocument/home-affairs-committee/the-work-of-the-home-secretary/oral/71645.html</a>).</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-09T16:48:40.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782817/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782817/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Home Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of her Department's preparations for the UK leaving the EU with (a) an agreement on future partnership and (b) no agreement with the EU; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","111212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782819","Home Office","false","2017-11-08","<p>Visa income is not differentiated between the various categories in which they are received.</p><p>Visa volumes by broad category (study, work etc) are published in the data section of this webpage: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-january-to-march-2017/why-do-people-come-to-the-uk-3-to-study#data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-january-to-march-2017/why-do-people-come-to-the-uk-3-to-study#data-tables</a></p><p>Fees and unit costs are also published, for example, for 2017/18:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/606616/Unit_cost_table_2017.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/606616/Unit_cost_table_2017.pdf</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-08T14:54:29.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782819/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782819/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Visas: Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much was accrued to the public purse from charging international students applying for Tier 4 student visas in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","111112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782821","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Home Office collects information on the number of hate crimes recorded by the police, by monitored strand. The latest statistics are published in the ‘Hate crime, England and Wales, 2016 to 2017’ statistical bulletin, available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/hate-crime-england-and-wales-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/hate-crime-england-and-wales-2016-to-2017</a></p><p>This Government is committed to tackling hate crime. The UK has a strong legislative framework to tackle hate crime. We are working across Government with police, (including National Community Tensions Team), the Crown Prosecution Service and community partners to send out a clear message that hate crime will not be tolerated and we will vigorously pursue and prosecute those who commit these crimes.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-11-07T15:54:27.96Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782821/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782821/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Hate Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many incidents have been recorded in each category of hate crime in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","111085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782822","Home Office","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Home Office constantly reviews its capabilities and resources in order to deliver the priorities of the Government. The Department responded quickly to the challenges following the EU referendum last June.</p><p>Negotiations are continuing with our EU partners and we will update and finalise our plans on the workforce and capabilities required to manage the transition of non-UK EU nationals to settled status in due course.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-08T14:36:35.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782822/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782822/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many additional staff her Department plans to (a) recruit and (b) contract to manage the transition of non-UK EU nationals to settled status.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","111113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782823","Home Office","false","2017-11-06","<p>The Disclosure and Baring Service (DBS) has a governance framework set out in the Protection of Freedoms Act 2012 and a performance framework agreed with the Home Office. The DBS regularly reports on performance and risk to its Board and Home Office Ministers.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-11-06T17:28:59.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782823/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782823/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to improve the Disclosure and Barring Service checking service.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","111100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782824","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Home Office is working closely with the Metropolitan Police and Greater Manchester Police to help manage the cost of the immediate response to the recent attacks.</p><p> </p><p>The Metropolitan Police are currently preparing an application for Special Grant to support the financial consequences of the terrorist attacks at Westminster and London Bridge.</p><p> </p><p>The Mayor of Greater Manchester has applied for Special Grant to support the financial consequences of the terrorist attack on the Manchester Arena.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","111107","2017-11-07T10:29:26.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782824/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782824/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Terrorism: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether the Metropolitan Police has submitted a special grant request for the terrorist attacks at (a) Westminster and (b) London Bridge.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","111106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782825","Home Office","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Home Office publishes quarterly figures on the number of asylum seekers housed in dispersed accommodation, including under Section 95, by local authority in the Immigration Statistics release, in table as_16q and 17q in volume 4 of the Asylum data tables. These are available at:<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-11-09T16:28:26.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782825/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782825/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum seeker placements each local authority has had in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","111076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782827","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>Staff in the Department can utilise the Westminster Holiday Play Scheme. This is a childcare facility that takes place during school holidays, open to children from the age of 4 years and 9 months up to 15 years’ old. It is run by a private company on behalf of a consortium of departments, through a contract led and administered by BEIS. It currently operates at 4 London locations. Parents/guardians meet more than half of the costs for children attending this scheme, but the Department pays either £14.78 or £15.68 (dependent on the age of the child) towards each day’s use of the scheme.</p><p>During FY 2016/17, Home Office has recorded spend of £4045.84 on this play scheme. The Department does not collate details on the number of individual staff members who made use of the scheme or on the amounts spent per child.</p><p>More widely, the Home Office operates a Childcare Voucher Salary Sacrifice Scheme for staff. Staff can choose to take part of their salary (up to £243 per month) in the form of childcare vouchers. As the vouchers are exempt from Tax and NI, a saving is made. The vouchers can be used to help meet the costs of a range of registered childcare.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-11-07T14:59:42.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782827/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782827/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Home Office: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what childcare facilities her Department makes available for its staff; how much her Department spent (a) overall and (b) per child on those facilities in the last 12 months; and how many of her Department's staff use those facilities.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","111064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782828","Home Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Home Office is working closely with the Metropolitan Police and Greater Manchester Police to help manage the cost of the immediate response to the recent attacks.</p><p> </p><p>The Metropolitan Police are currently preparing an application for Special Grant to support the financial consequences of the terrorist attacks at Westminster and London Bridge.</p><p> </p><p>The Mayor of Greater Manchester has applied for Special Grant to support the financial consequences of the terrorist attack on the Manchester Arena.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","111106","2017-11-07T10:29:26.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782828/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782828/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Terrorism: Manchester Arena","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether Greater Manchester Police has submitted a special grant request in relation to the terrorist attacks at Manchester Arena.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","111107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782829","Home Office","false","2018-02-12","<p>Asylum seekers are not allowed to work in the UK unless their claim has been outstanding for at least 12 months through no fault of their own. The policy is designed to protect the resident labour market so that access to employment is prioritised for British citizens and lawful residents, including those granted refugees status. We have no plans to change this policy.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-12T12:00:12.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782829/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782829/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-11-02","Asylum: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment the Government has made of the potential merits of allowing asylum seekers to work while their application is progressing.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","111061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782830","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-07","<p>DFID has 2 HQ buildings in the UK, one in Whitehall and one in East Kilbride. Neither building provides childcare facilities however DFID operates the Childcare Voucher scheme to assist parents of young children with the cost of nursery and after school placements.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-11-07T16:17:09.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782830/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782830/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-02","Department for International Development: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what childcare facilities her Department makes available for its staff; how much her Department spent (a) overall and (b) per child on those facilities in the last 12 months; and how many of her Department's staff use those facilities.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","111063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782832","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Gaza Reconstruction Mechanism (GRM) has been successful in importing construction materials to facilitate the reconstruction of buildings damaged during the 2014 conflict. Over 170,000 people have been able to carry out repairs and over 14,000 fully or partially damaged homes have been rebuilt. UN reports assess that the GRM has been less successful in facilitating the import of other “dual-use” materials; and that it is critical that the import of more “dual-use” items is simplified and expedited in order to facilitate larger infrastructure projects. A more comprehensive lifting of restrictions on materials entering Gaza, as part of a political agreement, is the only long-term solution.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-11-09T10:42:16.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782832/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782832/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-02","Gaza: Reconstruction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the Gaza Reconstruction Mechanism and the effect of the Israeli Government's dual-use list on reconstruction.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","111018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782833","Department for International Development","false","2017-11-09","<p>Following the referendum in June 2016, the Department for International Development continues to make rigorous preparations for a range of possible outcomes from the UK's negotiations with the EU.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-11-09T10:42:42.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782833/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782833/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-11-02","Department for International Development: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of her Department's preparations for the UK leaving the EU with (a) an agreement on future partnership and (b) no agreement with the EU; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","111213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782834","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-10","<p>All 21 Community Rehabilitation Companies have had their contracts amended so they can focus on activities that best rehabilitate offenders and keep society safe. This additional investment will see projected payments to providers being no higher than originally budgeted for at the time of the reforms.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-10T14:22:55.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782834/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782834/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-02","Community Rehabilitation Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Written Statement of 19 July 2017, HCWS81, on Justice Update, which community rehabilitation companies have had their contracts amended.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","111228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782835","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-10","<p>Following the referendum in June 2016,The MoJ continues to make rigorous preparations for a range of possible outcomes from the UK's negotiations with the EU.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-10T14:49:11.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782835/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782835/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-02","Ministry of Justice: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of his Department's preparations for the UK leaving the EU with (a) an agreement on future partnership and (b) no agreement with the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","111215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782837","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-07","<p>The cost to the public purse of the closures of Oldham Magistrates’ and County Court is as follows.</p><p> </p><p>Oldham County Court</p><p>Full exit on 15 September 2017</p><p>Lease ended on 17 September 2017</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>(i) Removal of fixtures and fittings (decant and porterage; excludes IT decommissioning, which is captured in “other costs” below)</p></td><td><p>£35,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(ii) Remaining lease payments</p></td><td><p>None – lease exited 17 Sept 2017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(iii) Dilapidations</p></td><td><p>Unknown – negotiations are ongoing with landlord</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(iv) Ongoing security and utilities</p></td><td><p>£630 (total cost between exit and disposal)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(v) Other costs</p></td><td><p>£116,800</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Dilapidations are commercially sensitive as works are not yet complete.</p><p> </p><p>Oldham Magistrates’ Court</p><p>Full exit on 20 March 2017</p><p>Disposal on 1 April 2017</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>(i) Removal of fixtures and fittings (decant and porterage; excludes IT decommissioning which is captured in “other costs” below)</p></td><td><p>£15,700</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(ii) Remaining lease payments</p></td><td><p>N/A freehold</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(iii) Dilapidations</p></td><td><p>N/A freehold</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(iv) Ongoing security and utilities</p></td><td><p>£2,500 (total cost between exit and disposal)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(v) Other costs</p></td><td><p>£70,800</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Costs provided are estimates. Other costs include IT decommissioning, excess travel fares to staff (based on an expectation that these will be paid for three years) and disposal costs (Oldham Magistrates’ Court only – fees). These costs are considered to be at a normal level for courts of this nature.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-11-07T17:10:16.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782837/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782837/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-02","Courts: Oldham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of the closures of (a) Oldham Magistrates Court and (b) Oldham County Court broken down by (i) removal of fixtures and fittings, (ii) remaining lease payments, (iii) dilapidation (iv) ongoing security and utilities and (v) other costs.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","111122"
