"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782844","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-10","<p>The Ministry has several statutory obligations to provide interpretation and translation in criminal proceedings for defendants.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry is committed to ensuring the justice system is supported by a range of high quality language services that meet the needs of all those that require them. My officials monitor demand for these services and work with our suppliers to ensure the requests of these services are met. The latest official statistics published in September 2017, shows 98% of language service assessments are fulfilled.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-10T14:49:52.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782844/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782844/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-02","Trials: Translation Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the level of take-up by defendants of their right to be tried in a language they understand.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","111195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782845","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-10","<p>During 2014 extensive work was undertaken to transfer MoJ’s higher rate customer service lines into local rate numbers. Since that time the responsibility for these lines has been devolved to the ALBs and MOJ does not hold any information centrally, in this regard.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-10T14:23:37.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782845/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782845/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-02","Ministry of Justice: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many and what proportion of his Department's public phone-lines charge members of the public to call.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","111090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782847","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-10","<p>The UK is a world leader in the provision of legal services and English law has a reputation for excellence across the world. The reputation of the UK’s Courts, Judiciary and legal services sector will continue after we leave the EU, and we will build on this to make the most of the opportunities of post-Brexit global Britain. We also continue to promote our excellent legal services overseas, and launched our ‘Legal Services are GREAT’ campaign last month, to highlight the UK’s position as a premier legal centre.”</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-10T14:48:45.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782847/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782847/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-02","Legal Profession","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans he has to support the UK legal services sector before and after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","111142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782848","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>Information on how many prisoners waited more than 14 days to be transferred to a secure hospital since 2010 is not available in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>The Prison Transfer and Remission Guidance, published by the Department in 2011, is currently being reviewed by NHS England. The particular focus of this work is on ensuring that the timescales within the Guidance take into account clinical urgency and need.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","111020","2017-11-08T17:48:50.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782848/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782848/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-02","Prisoners: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the number of prisoners who are waiting no more than 14 days to be admitted to a secure hospital.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","111019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782849","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>Information on how many prisoners waited more than 14 days to be transferred to a secure hospital since 2010 is not available in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>The Prison Transfer and Remission Guidance, published by the Department in 2011, is currently being reviewed by NHS England. The particular focus of this work is on ensuring that the timescales within the Guidance take into account clinical urgency and need.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","111019","2017-11-08T17:48:50.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782849/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782849/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-02","Prisoners: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many prisoners waited more than 14 days to be transferred to a secure hospital since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","111020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782850","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-10","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that prison officers receive the appropriate training to support prisoners with mental health needs. The Prison Officer Entry Level Training (POELT) course, delivered to new Prison Officers, includes modules on mental health and personality disorders which emphasise the importance of mental health awareness.</p><p> </p><p>The revised “Introduction to Suicide and Self-Harm (SASH) Prevention” training includes a refreshed mental health awareness module. This training is being delivered to all new and existing Prison Officers and non-HMPPS staff who come into contact with prisoners.</p><p> </p><p>A Suicide Prevention Learning Tool has also been developed in partnership with Samaritans to support our suicide prevention and self-harm work. This tool communicates important messages to identify and support prisoners at risk.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-10T14:48:15.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782850/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782850/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-02","Prisoners: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans he has for training prison officers to receive improved training on mental health conditions.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","111021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782852","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>NHS England signed a contract on 20 October 2017 for an enhanced IT system for prison clinical records. The Health and Justice Information Service (HJIS) will introduce a similar data-sharing approach to that used in the community when a patient changes their general practitioner (GP).</p><p> </p><p>HJIS will enable people in prisons, immigration removal centres and the secure children and young people’s estate (collectively referred to as the “residential estate”) to be registered, via the NHS Spine, with the healthcare service in the residential estate.</p><p> </p><p>In future, once the new functionality is deployed, it will be possible for the patient’s clinical records to be transferred from the community for use in the residential estate, and when they leave, for the updated record to be retrieved in the community when they register again with a community GP.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-11-08T17:51:03.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782852/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782852/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-02","Prisons: Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress his Department is making on linking prison health records to community GPs.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","111022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782853","Department of Health","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Basic Custody Screening Tool is an initial questionnaire that is used by the offender management unit within 72 hours of entry into prison and can identify prisoners suitable for referral to mental health services. The information recorded here is not designed to make a clinical assessment of mental health need.</p><p> </p><p>New prisoners are also assessed by healthcare staff on their reception into prison in order to ascertain what urgent needs they may have to keep them safe in their first hours in custody. Every prisoner who is screened as requiring further mental health support will then be referred to the mental health team within the establishment.</p><p> </p><p>Prisoners also receive a further comprehensive assessment within 72 hours which would prompt further assessments or urgent treatment for any physical health, mental health and/or substance misuse needs. Prisoners will then have a second-stage assessment within seven days of their reception, which will assess their needs in more detail.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is currently working across the entire criminal justice pathway to improve services for offenders with mental health difficulties. In line with the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health, and the Strategic Direction for Health and Justice, NHS England is working with partners to intervene at the earliest opportunity to ensure that offenders receive the right care, in the right place, at the right time. These specific mental health services will be available to prisoners across the estate where assessment identifies treatment needs.</p><p> </p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-11-08T17:46:14.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782853/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782853/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-11-02","Prisoners: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent steps he has taken to better identify prisoners who require mental health services.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","111023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782854","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-07","<p>There are no on-site childcare facilities provided by the Ministry of Justice on its estate. However, the Department recognises that employees need flexible pre-school and out-of-school childcare of a type and in a location most convenient to them, and we offer a salary sacrifice scheme for childcare vouchers. This enables employees to choose their own childcare provider (subject to meeting eligibility requirements) and have their childcare costs reduced by taking part of their salary in the form of childcare vouchers, which are exempt from tax and National Insurance contributions.</p><p>We also offer a range of flexible working options to staff, including term-time working, job shares and compressed hours, to allow staff with caring responsibilities to work in the way that best suits them.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-11-07T17:51:58.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782854/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782854/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-02","Ministry of Justice: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what childcare facilities his Department makes available for its staff; how much his Department (a) overall and (b) per child on those facilities in the last 12 months; and how many of his Department's staff use those facilities.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","111072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782856","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-10","<table><tbody><tr><td><p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>All judicial training is the responsibility of senior judiciary and this is exercised through the Judicial College who have provided the following information. The First-tier Tribunal and Upper Tribunal (Composition of Tribunals) Order 2008 and the Senior President’s Practise Statement provides that all PIP appeals, subject to limited exceptions must be heard by a judge and a medical and disability qualified members. All tribunal members in the Social Security and Child Support jurisdiction (with the exception of financially qualified Tribunal members) are trained to hear PIP appeals. The table below shows a combined number for both the judges and panel member training. <strong> </strong> <strong>Number of Judicial Office Holders receiving training in PIP from 01/01/13 by quarter</strong> (The number of active Judicial Office Holder’s (JOHs) has oscillated between approximately 1800 and 2000 over the period in question.)</p></td></tr></tbody></table></p></td></tr></tbody></table>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-10T14:50:39.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782856/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782856/answer","PQ 111234  Table.doc","PQ 111234  Table.doc","Table","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782856/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-02","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 30 October 2017 to Question 109400, if he will publish the number of judicial office holders trained for personal independence payment tribunals in each quarter since 2 January 2013.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","111234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782857","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-08","<p>This information is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Every self-inflicted death in prison custody is independently investigated by the Prisons and Probation Ombudsman (PPO) and is the subject of a coroner’s inquest. We take the findings of these investigations very seriously. Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service works with healthcare partners to ensure that action is taken to address the recommendations made by the PPO, and any matters of concern brought to our attention by coroners, including any that relate to the provision of medication or therapies for mental health conditions.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-08T19:48:43.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782857/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782857/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-02","Prisoners: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 30 October 2017 to Question 109680, on prisons: suicide, how many and what proportion of self-inflicted deaths were prisoners (a) on medication for mental health issues and (b) participating in talking therapies at the time of their death.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","111248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782858","Leader of the House","false","2017-11-07","<p>As set out in my Written Ministerial Statement of 26 October, the Government will respond to Opposition day resolutions within 12 weeks. It is intended that Ministers will attend the Chamber wherever possible but a Written Ministerial Statement may be provided from time to time.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2017-11-07T13:31:12.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782858/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782858/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2017-11-02","Opposition Days: Government Responses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, pursuant to the Written Ministerial Statement of 26 October 2017, HCWS 199, on Opposition Day debates, whether a ministerial response to a resolution of the House will take the form of a Written or Oral Statement.","false","Biography information for Paula Sherriff","Dewsbury","Paula Sherriff","111110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782859","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>A response to the British Association of Social Workers will issue this week.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-11-07T10:44:40.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782859/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782859/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-11-02","Northern Ireland Office: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, when he plans to respond to the letter of 4 July 2017 from the British Association of Social Workers on universal credit specific circumstances and the Criminal Law Act (Northern Ireland) 1967.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","111057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782861","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-11-13","<p>The role of the Northern Ireland Office (NIO) is to ensure the smooth working of the political settlement in Northern Ireland. It represents Northern Ireland interests within the UK Government and represents the UK government interests and policy in Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p>Accordingly, responsibility for relevant policies including border, customs and immigration is held by other Whitehall Government Departments and the Northern Ireland Executive rather than by NIO. My officials however are working with officials across government, in close coordination with the Department for Exiting the European Union, to ensure that appropriate preparations have been made and plans are in place for all scenarios.</p><p> </p><p>The UK Government is determined to make a success of Exit for the whole of the UK, including Northern Ireland.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-11-13T10:58:58.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782861/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782861/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-11-02","Northern Ireland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of his Department's preparations for the UK leaving the EU with (a) an agreement on future partnership and (b) no agreement with the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","111216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782862","Prime Minister","false","2017-11-10","<p>I visit all parts of the United Kingdom regularly. Details of my visits within the United Kingdom are published on the gov.uk website.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-11-10T12:37:32.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782862/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782862/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-11-02","Prime Minister: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, pursuant to the Answer of 15 September to Question 9602, on how many occasions she has visited Easington constituency since she became Prime Minister.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","111201"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782864","Prime Minister","false","2017-11-10","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by the First Secretary of State and Minister for the Cabinet Office, my right hon. Friend the Member for Ashford (Mr Green) on 2 November 2017, UIN 109813.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-11-10T12:36:42.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782864/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782864/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-11-02","Prime Minister: Italy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what the total cost to the public purse was of the visit by the Prime Minister, ministers and officials to Florence on 22 October 2017.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","111249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782865","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The tolls on the Humber Bridge were introduced to help pay for the costs of constructing the Bridge, which opened in 1981. Construction was financed through a loan from the Government of the day.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012, the present Government wrote off £150m of the £332m debt In order to reduce tolls and encourage use of the Bridge. Since then, the number of vehicles using the Bridge has increased significantly.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015, the Humber Bridge Board refinanced the remaining debt of £172m with a Public Works Board Loan. The Government has not made an estimate of the costs of abolishing tolls on the Humber Bridge, since the operation and financing of the remaining debt of the Humber Bridge is the responsibility for the Board and its constituent authorities.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","111238 ; 111246","2017-11-08T10:59:55.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782865/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782865/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Humber Bridge: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the cost to the public purse would be of abolishing fees on the Humber Bridge.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","111245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782866","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The tolls on the Humber Bridge were introduced to help pay for the costs of constructing the Bridge, which opened in 1981. Construction was financed through a loan from the Government of the day.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012, the present Government wrote off £150m of the £332m debt In order to reduce tolls and encourage use of the Bridge. Since then, the number of vehicles using the Bridge has increased significantly.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015, the Humber Bridge Board refinanced the remaining debt of £172m with a Public Works Board Loan. The Government has not made an estimate of the costs of abolishing tolls on the Humber Bridge, since the operation and financing of the remaining debt of the Humber Bridge is the responsibility for the Board and its constituent authorities.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","111238 ; 111245","2017-11-08T10:59:55.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782866/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782866/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Humber Bridge: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for what reasons the Government introduced fees on the Humber Bridge; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","111246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782867","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The tolls on the Humber Bridge were introduced to help pay for the costs of constructing the Bridge, which opened in 1981. Construction was financed through a loan from the Government of the day.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012, the present Government wrote off £150m of the £332m debt In order to reduce tolls and encourage use of the Bridge. Since then, the number of vehicles using the Bridge has increased significantly.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015, the Humber Bridge Board refinanced the remaining debt of £172m with a Public Works Board Loan. The Government has not made an estimate of the costs of abolishing tolls on the Humber Bridge, since the operation and financing of the remaining debt of the Humber Bridge is the responsibility for the Board and its constituent authorities.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","111245 ; 111246","2017-11-08T10:59:55.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782867/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782867/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Humber Bridge: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to (a) reduce and (b) abolish fees for customers on the Humber Bridge; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","111238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782868","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Secretary of State meets regularly with the leadership team of Network Rail to discuss progress on a range of topics including releasing surplus land.</p><p> </p><p>Both the Secretary of State for Transport and Network Rail are committed to releasing land for housing where possible. Network Rail is delivering a detailed programme of sales nationally to free up land for housing and to generate proceeds that can be reinvested into the railway.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-11-07T11:40:47.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782868/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782868/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Network Rail: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what representations he has made to Network Rail on the sale of surplus land in its ownership.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","111154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782869","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-07","<p>The new lines between Bedford and Corby will support speeds of up to 125mph for passenger trains. The existing lines between St Pancras and Bedford currently support speeds of up to 100 mph for electric passenger trains, and we are developing plans to adjust the Overhead Line Equipment on this section in order to enable the new trains coming into service on the Midland Main Line to run at the improved line speeds.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-11-07T13:10:39.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782869/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782869/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Railways: Bedfordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the line speeds are for the (a) newly installed sections north of Bedford to Corby and (b) existing electric infrastructure south of Bedfordshire into London St. Pancras.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","111128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782871","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-07","<p>Decisions about where and how to invest in transport are guided by the business case approach. This involves taking a range of strategic and economic factors into consideration in a fair and rigorous way, and ensures transport capital investment goes where it is most needed.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not make assessments on the equity of the distribution of historic transport capital investment across regions. But ministers have long recognised historic underinvestment in transport infrastructure, especially in the North.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-11-07T12:51:27.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782871/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782871/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Public Transport: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the equity of the distribution of transport capital investment in each region in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","111123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782872","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-07","<p>No firm decision on rail services in the next East Midlands franchise has yet been taken. The next franchise starts in August 2019. Invitations to Tender are due to be issued to potential bidders in April 2018. All options for rail services in the next franchise are subject to analysis of the potential benefits and our consultation with stakeholders, which closed on 11 October.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-11-07T13:02:07.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782872/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782872/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Railways: East Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if (a) peak and (b) off peak direct inter-city services to Sheffield, Derby and Nottingham will continue to stop at (i) Luton, (ii) Bedford and (iii) Wellingborough as a result of the proposed changes to the East Midlands rail network.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","111127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782873","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-07","<p>The public consultation included proposals to improve intercity journey times between Sheffield (via Derby), Nottingham and London St Pancras by not stopping as often at stations used by commuters, such as Luton, Bedford, Wellingborough and Kettering. Passengers at these stations would instead be served by dedicated and more capacious high quality trains operating on the Corby–London route. The consultation sought views on these proposals given that, although the majority of passengers will benefit, a minority of passengers would need to change trains to complete their journeys as direct services would be reduced. We are currently reviewing the responses to that consultation and no decisions have been taken yet regarding the future timetable.</p><p><br>Both a) an equality impact assessment and b) a Kettering passenger number analysis will be carried out by the Department to inform this decision and we will publish them at the appropriate time.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-11-07T13:06:30.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782873/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782873/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Kettering Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will publish the (a) equality impact assessment and (b) feasibility studies on increased passenger numbers at Kettering railway station.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","111126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782874","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-09","<p>Following the referendum in June 2016, the Department for Transport continues to make rigorous preparations for a range of possible outcomes from the UK's negotiations with the EU.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-11-09T12:23:27.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782874/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782874/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Department for Transport: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of his Department's preparations for the UK leaving the EU with (a) an agreement on future partnership and (b) no agreement with the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","111217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782875","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-07","<p>Good progress was made and the Group has agreed in principle a recommendation to be submitted to myself before Christmas.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-11-07T15:39:31.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782875/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782875/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Shipping: Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 26 October 2017 to Question 109053, on shipping: minimum wage, what progress the legal working group made at its meeting on 1 November 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","111262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782877","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-07","<p>In recognition of the breadth of perspectives and needs which the task and finish group on taxi and private hire vehicle licensing must consider in its review of sector issues, the terms of reference were designed to ensure that evidence could be taken from external parties. The group has recognised the importance of the sector to disabled people by already taking written evidence from the Disabled Persons Transport Advisory Committee, the Guide Dogs for the Blind Association, and the National Association of Taxi Users.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-11-07T15:42:09.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782877/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782877/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Taxis: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the task and finish group on taxi and private hire vehicle licensing will invite disabled people and organisations representing disabled people to give evidence.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","111254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782878","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-07","<p>The terms of reference and membership of the task and finish group on taxi and private hire vehicle licensing were designed to bring together a small but broadly representative group of sector stakeholders, to consider current issues and produce recommendations for action. In recognition of the breadth of perspectives that the group would need to consider, the terms of reference were specifically designed to ensure that the group would have the ability to invite others to provide evidence. To that end, the group has already taken written evidence from a range of organisations including the Disabled Persons Transport Advisory Committee, the Guide Dogs for the Blind Association, and the National Association of Taxi Users.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-11-07T15:36:47.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782878/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782878/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Taxis: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how his Department took account of the needs of disabled people when it set out the terms of reference and membership of the task and finish group on taxi and private hire vehicle licensing.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","111255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782879","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>Lifeboat provision in the UK is delivered by independent charitable organisations who declare their lifeboats available to Her Majesty’s Coastguard (HMCG). It is the responsibility of those organisations to decide on the specific operational capacity it considers appropriate based on factors such as coastal activity and the availability and suitability of other declared rescue assets covering that area.</p><p> </p><p>Search and rescue (SAR) response in the United Kingdom relies on a matrix of resources including SAR helicopters, lifeboats, community-based Coastguard Rescue Teams, commercial shipping, fishing and other vessels in the vicinity of an incident, and potentially other emergency services. In coordinating a response to any incident, HMCG will consider the range of resources available to them, on an incident by-incident basis, before tasking the most appropriate asset.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-11-08T10:37:53.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782879/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782879/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Lifeboats","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which areas of the UK coastline have no lifeboat coverage within a one hour journey time.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","111050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782880","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Department, including its Agencies, has 3,187 public phone-lines. The vast majority of these lines are for the general public to make enquiries at the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (more than 40 numbers using over 1500 lines) and at the Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (for example at driving test centres).</p><p> </p><p>Fewer than 1% of those phone lines are free to the caller (via an 0800 number). However, the charges otherwise paid by the caller from a landline will in virtually all cases be at the standard or local rate. Whilst the DVLA publicise two premium rate numbers which the general public can call for translation services, this means that apart from those the Department including its Agencies makes no income from their phone lines for the general public to call.</p><p> </p><p>Charges may be different for a mobile phone depending upon the rate that the relevant network operator imposes, though many people have a free calls allowance as part of their mobile phone package.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-11-08T10:41:46.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782880/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782880/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Department for Transport: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many and what proportion of his Department's public phone-lines charge members of the public to call.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","111089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782881","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-08","<p>Ministers have pressed Volkswagen to apply the technical fix to vehicles in the UK (including Northern Ireland) as quickly as possible and to make it as easy as possible for owners to have this work completed. Officials meet monthly with the company to discuss their progress. Volkswagen have now applied the technical measure to around 800,000 of the 1.2m affected vehicles.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-11-08T10:50:27.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782881/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782881/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Volkswagen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has had discussions with representatives of Volkswagen on the timetable for the completion of the required emissions and technological repair work for affected vehicles in (a) Northern Ireland and (b) the UK.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","111008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782882","Department for Transport","false","2017-11-07","<p>After considerable work with the UK Laser working group and across Whitehall, the Vehicle Technology and Aviation Bill contained clauses making it an offence to shine or direct a laser at a vehicle, designed to strengthen existing legislation to address the risk of lasers being used maliciously against aircraft and other vehicles.</p><p> </p><p>Unfortunately the Vehicle Technology and Aviation Bill fell upon prorogation. To provide further certainty to pilots and the wider public, the Department for Transport is continuing to look at other legislative vehicles to strengthen existing legislation.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-11-07T12:22:58.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782882/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782882/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-11-02","Aviation: Lasers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will introduce legislative proposals to address the shining of lasers at aircraft and other vehicles.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","111000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782884","Wales Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>The £4.7 billion increase in research and development funding over the next 4 years is a UK wide programme that will award funding based on the quality of applications. Wales is home to world class research and innovation and my department is working hard to ensure as many applications as possible are received from Wales.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-11-07T10:43:20.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782884/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782884/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782884/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-11-02","Research: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what proportion of the additional £4.7 billion announced by the Government in April 2017 for investment in research and development funding his Department plans to allocate to businesses in Wales.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","111115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782885","Wales Office","false","2017-11-07","<p>As part of our work preparing to make a success of our departure from the European Union we are carrying out a full suite of economic analysis.</p><p> </p><p>We want our future relationship with the EU to be a deep and special partnership, taking in both economic and security cooperation. We are confident that a future partnership between the UK and EU is in the interests of both sides, so we approach these negotiations anticipating success. We do not want or expect a no deal outcome. However, we have a duty to plan for an alternative to the unlikely scenario in which no mutually satisfactory agreement can be reached</p><p> </p><p>I will continue to work with other Government departments, my expert panel of stakeholders, the Welsh Government, and the National Assembly for Wales, to support the Welsh economy and promote a prosperous Wales within a strong United Kingdom.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-11-07T16:19:12.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782885/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782885/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-11-02","Economic Situation: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what comparative assessment his Department has made of the proportional effect of leaving the EU with no deal on the Welsh and UK economies.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","111256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782886","Women and Equalities","false","2017-11-07","<p>We announced on 23 July that we will be consulting on changes to the Gender Recognition Act. We are currently developing the consultation content with the intention to publish later this year.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-11-07T16:21:08.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782886/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782886/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782886/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-11-02","Gender Recognition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, whether the Government plans to bring forward legislative proposals during the 2017-18 Parliamentary session to change the process for officially recording a change of gender.","false","Biography information for Jo Stevens","Cardiff Central","Jo Stevens","111114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782887","Women and Equalities","false","2017-11-10","<p>The Department for Education, including the Government Equalities Office, operates nine principal public phone lines. Calls to five of these lines are charged as UK-wide (0370), geographic (020) or public body (0300) numbers. Four of these are free-phone (0800 or 0808) numbers, which do not incur a charge.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-11-10T14:54:58.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782887/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782887/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782887/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-11-02","Government Equalities Office: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many and what proportion of her Department's public phone-lines charge members of the public to call.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","111088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782888","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-07","<p>The eligibility criteria, and the number of recipients and costs of passported benefits is a matter for the responsible department or the devolved administrations.</p><p> </p><p>Where the passported benefit includes one of the legacy benefits, Universal Credit has been added to the eligibility criteria so that people who claim the new benefit can continue to qualify.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","110992","2017-11-07T16:14:02.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782888/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782888/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782888/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what eligibility criteria are planned for each passported benefit for applicants for universal credit.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","110991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782889","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-07","<p>The eligibility criteria, and the number of recipients and costs of passported benefits is a matter for the responsible department or the devolved administrations.</p><p> </p><p>Where the passported benefit includes one of the legacy benefits, Universal Credit has been added to the eligibility criteria so that people who claim the new benefit can continue to qualify.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","110991","2017-11-07T16:14:02.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782889/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782889/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782889/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which passported benefits are dependent on receipt of a benefit being merged within universal credit; how many people received each such passported benefit in each of the last three financial years; and what the total cost was of those benefits in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","110992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782891","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-09","<p>Charges to the Department for Work and Pensions are not set by the Department but are applied by service providers and are dependent upon individual’s telephone contract. The Department for Work and Pensions does not have access to individual customer telephone call data that would establish if a call attracted a charge.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-11-09T14:09:35.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782891/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782891/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782891/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","Department for Work and Pensions: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of his Department's public phone-lines charge members of the public to call.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","111087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782892","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-09","<p>The information is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The latest information to February 2017 on the number of Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) claimants by phase of claim is published and available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-11-09T12:28:33.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782892/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782892/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782892/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many recipients of employment support allowance have moved into work since changes were made to the level of that benefit in April 2017.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","111083"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782893","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-07","<p>We are committed to processing all claims as quickly as possible, while ensuring we have all the evidence we need to make the right decisions. In Personal Independence Payment around 81,000 claims are processed each month compared with 80,000 per month this time last year. As at July 2017 the average claimant was waiting 8 weeks for an assessment for both new and reassessment claims. Where a claimant is terminally ill, their claim is fast tracked, these cases are currently taking just 6 working days to clear.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-11-07T14:58:31.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782893/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782893/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","Social Security Benefits: Motor Neurone Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to ensure the prompt payment of benefits to people with motor neurone disease; whether his Department plans to make changes to that regime for such people; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","111059"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782894","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-07","<p>The information asked for is not available in the format requested.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-07T18:05:56.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782894/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782894/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the (a) shortest, (b) average and (c) longest time taken from first contact to receipt of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","111056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782895","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-07","<p>We do not have any target times, but aim to deal with any case as quickly as possible paying arrears where necessary. The times taken to process appeal decisions post hearing are not available.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-11-07T11:24:10.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782895/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782895/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","Social Security Benefits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the Department's target times are for getting disability benefits claims back into payment after a tribunal rules in a claimant's favour; and what the times achieved were in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","111163"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782897","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>Direct comparisons between the old State Pension and the new State Pension are not appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>People reaching State Pension age before 6 April 2016 could be entitled to a basic State Pension and an additional State Pension. The full amount of the basic State Pension (£122.30 a week for 2017/18) was reached after 30 qualifying years of National Insurance contributions or credits. The amount of additional State Pension was based on earnings over a full working life and its value ranges from £0.01p a week to over £160 a week. Legislation requires that the basic State Pension is uprated by at least the increase in earnings each year and the additional State Pension by at least the increase in prices.</p><p> </p><p>The new State Pension replaced the old system for people reaching State Pension age from 6 April 2016 with a single pension which, after a transition period which recognises people’s National Insurance records in the old system, will require 35 qualifying years to achieve the full amount of £159.55 a week. Legislation requires the new State Pension is uprated by at least earnings each year.</p><p> </p><p>As set out in <em>The single-tier pension: a simple foundation for saving (Command 8528), </em>the objective of the new State Pension is to provide a foundation for private saving by individuals and is designed to deliver an amount set at or above the level of the weekly means test which most people should be able to achieve. The new State Pension system has been designed to provide a simpler, sustainable system for decades to come, correcting some of the historic unfairness in the previous system, in particular for women, self-employed people and lower paid workers.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","111220 ; 111224","2017-11-06T16:36:38.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782897/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782897/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons claimants are required to have 35 years of national insurance contributions instead of 30 years to qualify for the new state pension.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","111223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782898","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>Direct comparisons between the old State Pension and the new State Pension are not appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>People reaching State Pension age before 6 April 2016 could be entitled to a basic State Pension and an additional State Pension. The full amount of the basic State Pension (£122.30 a week for 2017/18) was reached after 30 qualifying years of National Insurance contributions or credits. The amount of additional State Pension was based on earnings over a full working life and its value ranges from £0.01p a week to over £160 a week. Legislation requires that the basic State Pension is uprated by at least the increase in earnings each year and the additional State Pension by at least the increase in prices.</p><p> </p><p>The new State Pension replaced the old system for people reaching State Pension age from 6 April 2016 with a single pension which, after a transition period which recognises people’s National Insurance records in the old system, will require 35 qualifying years to achieve the full amount of £159.55 a week. Legislation requires the new State Pension is uprated by at least earnings each year.</p><p> </p><p>As set out in <em>The single-tier pension: a simple foundation for saving (Command 8528), </em>the objective of the new State Pension is to provide a foundation for private saving by individuals and is designed to deliver an amount set at or above the level of the weekly means test which most people should be able to achieve. The new State Pension system has been designed to provide a simpler, sustainable system for decades to come, correcting some of the historic unfairness in the previous system, in particular for women, self-employed people and lower paid workers.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","111220 ; 111223","2017-11-06T16:36:39.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782898/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782898/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans to bring the maximum amount for the old state pension in line with the new state pension.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","111224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782899","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>The new State Pension has a minimum qualifying period of ten years to ensure that only people who have made a significant economic and social contribution can become entitled. However, people who do not satisfy the Minimum Qualifying Period may be entitled to means tested benefits. For example, Pension Credit provides means tested support for low income pensioners and works by topping up any other income to a standard minimum amount and Housing Benefit provides support for rent for those on a low income.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-11-06T16:41:14.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782899/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782899/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the requirement for a person to have 10 years of qualifying national insurance contributions to receive any state pension on poverty and homelessness of people aged over 60 in (a) Wales and (b) the UK.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","111221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782900","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions is undertaking planning for all EU exit scenarios, as is prudent for such a significant issue, including working closely with the Department for Exiting the European Union to ensure consistency of plans across government.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-09T14:38:37.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782900/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782900/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","Department for Work and Pensions: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of his Department's preparations for the UK leaving the EU with (a) an agreement on future partnership and (b) no agreement with the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","111219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782901","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>The new State Pension was introduced for those persons reaching State Pension age on, or after, 6th April 2016. Our latest data on the number of qualifying years people have are for the 2015/16 financial year, so we do not yet have any data on the numbers of people reaching State Pension age under the new State Pension with less than 10 years of National Insurance contributions.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-11-06T16:48:34.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782901/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782901/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in (a) Ceredigion, (b) Wales and (c) the UK are not eligible for the new state pension due to having less than 10 years of National Insurance contributions.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","111222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782903","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-06","<p>Direct comparisons between the old State Pension and the new State Pension are not appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>People reaching State Pension age before 6 April 2016 could be entitled to a basic State Pension and an additional State Pension. The full amount of the basic State Pension (£122.30 a week for 2017/18) was reached after 30 qualifying years of National Insurance contributions or credits. The amount of additional State Pension was based on earnings over a full working life and its value ranges from £0.01p a week to over £160 a week. Legislation requires that the basic State Pension is uprated by at least the increase in earnings each year and the additional State Pension by at least the increase in prices.</p><p> </p><p>The new State Pension replaced the old system for people reaching State Pension age from 6 April 2016 with a single pension which, after a transition period which recognises people’s National Insurance records in the old system, will require 35 qualifying years to achieve the full amount of £159.55 a week. Legislation requires the new State Pension is uprated by at least earnings each year.</p><p> </p><p>As set out in <em>The single-tier pension: a simple foundation for saving (Command 8528), </em>the objective of the new State Pension is to provide a foundation for private saving by individuals and is designed to deliver an amount set at or above the level of the weekly means test which most people should be able to achieve. The new State Pension system has been designed to provide a simpler, sustainable system for decades to come, correcting some of the historic unfairness in the previous system, in particular for women, self-employed people and lower paid workers.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","111223 ; 111224","2017-11-06T16:36:38.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782903/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782903/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782903/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons the maximum amount available under the new state pension is higher than the maximum amount available under the old state pension.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","111220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782904","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-07","<p>The information requested is not available.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-11-07T11:30:09.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782904/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782904/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782904/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","Local Housing Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment the Government has made of the effect that freezing local housing allowance has had on the number of (a) tenants in rent arrears and (b) tenants in the private rented sector.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","111137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782905","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-07","<p>There are no plans to lift the four year Local Housing Allowance (LHA) freeze before April 2020.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises however that the impact of this measure varies across the country, especially in areas of high rental growth and in view of this 30 per cent of the savings from the LHA Freeze are being recycled to create Targeted Affordability Funding. This funding is used to increase LHA rates in areas where local rents have diverged the most. For example in 2017/18, 48 LHA rates have been increased by 3 per cent. Further Targeted Affordability Funding will be made available in 2018/19 and 2019/20.</p><p> </p><p>In addition since 2011, the Government has provided around £900 million in Discretionary Housing Payments to local authorities to protect vulnerable claimants and support households affected by different welfare reforms including the freeze to LHA rates.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-11-07T11:32:18.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782905/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782905/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782905/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","Local Housing Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he has any plans to review the freezing of local housing allowance rates.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","111138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782906","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-09","<p>The application for Keighley Community Led Local Development project is in the final stages of appraisal and a decision is expected by the end of November.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-11-09T14:30:04.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782906/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782906/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782906/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","EU Grants and Loans: Keighley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, by what date he expects a decision to be made on the community-led local development aid for Keighley CCLD.","false","Biography information for John Grogan","Keighley","John Grogan","111136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782907","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-09","<p>The average length of service of the 10 most highly paid officials in the Department is 16.9 years.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>In calculating the average length of service we have used each individual’s date of entry to the civil service and therefore the calculation may include periods of service with other Government Departments.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-11-09T14:12:57.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782907/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782907/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782907/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","Department for Work and Pensions: Length of Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average length of service is in his Department by its 10 most highly paid officials.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","111105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782908","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-09","<p>Whilst I have regular meetings with senior officials from HSE, there have been no specific discussions about the findings in the Workplace Health Expert Committee (WHEC) report: Risks of bakery work: the adverse effects of working in high temperatures and of occupational asthma.</p><p> </p><p>HSE receives an annual report from WHEC which includes any reports the committee has published. HSE, via its Chief Scientific Adviser, is due to provide a formal response to the next report in Spring 2018.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-11-09T14:42:03.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782908/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782908/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782908/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","Bakeries: Industrial Health and Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what discussions he has had with the Health and Safety Executive on the recommendations of the Workplace Health Expert Committee report on the risks of bakery work published in March 2017.","false","Biography information for Lisa Nandy","Wigan","Lisa Nandy","111239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782909","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-11-10","<p>Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunals Service currently only publishes waiting time information at national level.</p><p> </p><p>It can provide waiting time information at hearing centre and regional level, but cannot provide the breakdown requested.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-11-10T14:23:20.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782909/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782909/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782909/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-11-02","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 30 October 2017 to Question 109400, if he will publish the local personal independence payment areas and the relevant constituencies, with a longer than average waiting time.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","111233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782910","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-11-07","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-11-07T12:52:21.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782910/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782910/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782910/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-11-02","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of claimants of employment and support allowance are awarded payments through the exemption contained in paragraph 25(b) of the Employment and Support Allowance Regulations 2013.","false","Biography information for Ian Mearns","Gateshead","Ian Mearns","111235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782912","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Government fully recognises the importance to business and to the UK economy of being able to protect and enforce intellectual property rights (IPRs), nationally and internationally. A report by the EU IPO, <a href="https://euipo.europa.eu/tunnel-web/secure/webdav/guest/document_library/observatory/documents/IPContributionStudy/performance_in_the_European_Union/performance_in_the_European_Union_full.pdf" target="_blank">Intellectual property rights intensive industries and economic performance in the European Union</a>, estimated that the value of IP intensive industries to the UK economy was £5,664,168 million or 42.3% of Gross Value Added (GVA) between 2011 and 2013. In addition the Intellectual Property Office (IPO) commissioned the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) to develop a methodology and to deliver a benchmark on the levels and impact of counterfeiting to the UK. This study <a href="http://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/governance/trade-in-counterfeit-products-and-the-uk-economy_9789264279063-en" target="_blank">Trade in Counterfeit Products and the UK Economy</a> was published on 4 September 2017.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-11-09T14:20:12.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782912/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782912/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Intellectual Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the value to UK businesses of a legal framework to protect and enforce their intellectual property rights throughout the world.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","111140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782914","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-11-13","<p>The act of leaving the EU means that it is inevitable that elements of the EU’s supranational framework will not be retained.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The EU (Withdrawal) Bill will provide businesses and stakeholders with maximum certainty as we leave the European Union by ensuring that, wherever practical, the same rules and laws apply after exit and that legal rights and obligations are clear.</p><p> </p><p>We are also pursuing a deep and special future partnership with the EU, the exact nature of which will be determined by the outcome of the negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-11-13T15:49:16.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782914/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782914/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782914/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-11-02","EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on the compatibility of the UK and EU legal regimes after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","111141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782915","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-10","<p>Whilst the valuation process is ongoing, it would not be appropriate to publish the Government’s objectives.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-11-10T12:03:50.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782915/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782915/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782915/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Mineworkers' Pension Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 14 September 2017 to Question 9553, if he will publish the Government's objectives for the forthcoming Mineworkers' Pension scheme valuation.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","111202"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782917","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Government supports the use of baseline monitoring, which can be valuable in showing local communities environmental conditions ahead of operations, and helps ensure a more rigorous post-operation assessment.</p><p> </p><p>Environmental permits for shale gas sites set out conditions that require baseline monitoring as well as ongoing monitoring throughout operations. Baseline data is important in the understanding of existing local environmental conditions. Permit conditions seek to ensure that no unacceptable impacts are caused by operations on the environment.</p><p> </p><p>In the event that pollution is detected that can be attributed to permitted activities on any given site, action will be required to remediate any impact.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-11-07T16:01:41.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782917/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782917/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782917/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether it is Government policy to ensure that baseline levels of environmental pollution prior to any fracking are not exceeded; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","111191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782918","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-13","<p>As I previously set out in my answer to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-10-20/108898/" target="_blank">108898</a>, the Certification Officer is not in a position to disclose documentation on current or past cases. This means that any documentation related to the case of the National Union of Mineworkers: Northumberland remains in the custody of the Certification Officer on a confidential basis.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-11-13T10:51:23.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782918/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782918/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","National Union of Mineworkers: Northumberland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 25 October 2017 to Question 108898, on National Union of Mineworkers: Northumberland, if he will place the requested documentation in the Library.","false","Biography information for Ben Bradley","Mansfield","Ben Bradley","111203"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782919","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-08","<p>The Government is fully committed to negotiating a deep and special partnership with the European Union. The Department is preparing for future trade negotiations by building capability and resource, and is developing positions for a range of negotiating scenarios in order to minimise disruption for UK businesses and avoid the introduction of new regulatory barriers.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-11-08T12:59:15.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782919/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782919/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of his Department's preparations for the UK leaving the EU with (a) an agreement on future partnership and (b) no agreement with the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","111204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782920","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-07","<p>Ofgem’s Domestic Suppliers Social Obligation: 2011 Annual Report shows the average level of consumer debt held by energy consumers in 2010 was £360 for electricity and £339 for gas, and in 2011 £357 for electricity and £371 for gas. The Ofgem report ‘vulnerable consumers in the retail energy market 2017’ shows the average level of debt at the point customers start to repay “take-on debt” from 2012 to 2016. The methodology for reporting debt levels changed in 2012. This means it is not possible to provide a like for like comparison from 2010 through to 2016.</p><p>Figure 6 in the Ofgem report shows the average level of debt from 2012 to 2016, and can be found at: <a href="https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/system/files/docs/2017/10/consumer_vulnerability_report_web_003.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/system/files/docs/2017/10/consumer_vulnerability_report_web_003.pdf</a></p><p>The fuel poverty strategy has interim milestones to improve fuel poor homes to Band E by 2020 and Band D by 2025. This guides an approach to targeting the least energy efficient properties first, as they are facing the most severe problem. The latest official statistics show that there were 835,000 fewer E, F or G rated fuel poor homes in 2015 compared to 2010. This focus on the least energy efficient homes does mean that fewer D rated homes are improved to Band C, within the same budget. The latest statistics show that 8% of fuel poor households are were rated Band C or better in 2015 and this is projected to increase to 11% in 2017.</p><p>We will continue to make progress towards the fuel poverty milestones and 2030 target. The Clean Growth Strategy recently committed to at least £640m of support per year for home energy efficiency through to 2028 and we will be consulting in the new year on our proposals for the Energy Company Obligation (ECO) to run from 2018 to 2022. In parallel, we will be considering the best forms of support for home energy efficiency over the longer term for subsequent consultation.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-11-07T16:22:24.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782920/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782920/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782920/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the average level of outstanding household energy bill debt in each year since 2010; what estimate he has made of the number of fuel-poor households which will remain in properties insulated below Energy Performance Certificate Band C by 2030; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","111171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782921","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-09","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Under section 4A of the Petroleum Act 1998, all licensees are required to provide details of proposed plans to undertake 12 months' monitoring of the level of methane in groundwater, in line with the guidance[1] issued by the Department in February 2017.</p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/591631/Hydraulic_Fracturing_Consent_Guidance.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/591631/Hydraulic_Fracturing_Consent_Guidance.pdf</a></p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-11-09T14:06:12.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782921/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782921/answer","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782921/answer/previousversion/20977","Biography information for Richard Harrington","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 30 October 2017 to Question 109370, on fracking, and with reference to his Department's hydraulic fracturing consent guidance, published in February 2017, whether licensees seeking hydraulic fracturing consent (HFC) will be required to provide details in environmental permit applications of proposed plans to undertake 12 months' monitoring of the level of methane in groundwater in relation to (a) the current application for HFC for Ryedale, North Yorkshire and (b) all future such applications.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","111259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782922","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that the UK continues to lead the world in fusion research<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup>. Our recent future partnership paper<sup><sup>[2]</sup></sup> made clear our desire to continue to collaborate with the EU in this important field. The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy is working closely with the Department for Exiting the EU and the UK Atomic Energy Authority to engage constructively with our EU partners.</p><p>We have already taken action to help secure the future of the Joint European Torus (JET) facility by guaranteeing the UK’s share of JET costs until the end of 2020. The relevant Written Ministerial Statement can be found here: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2017-06-27/HCWS13/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-statement/Commons/2017-06-27/HCWS13/</a>.</p><p> </p><p>[1] A 2016 independent review by the Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC) found the UK fusion research programme to be ‘of world-class quality, in facilities, people and impact’.</p><p>[2] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/collaboration-on-science-and-innovation-a-future-partnership-paper" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/collaboration-on-science-and-innovation-a-future-partnership-paper</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-11-07T17:36:40.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782922/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782922/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Nuclear Fusion: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect the UK leaving the EU on nuclear fusion research in the UK.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","111253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782923","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that the UK continues to lead the world in fusion research[1]. Our recent future partnership paper[2] made clear our desire to continue to collaborate with the EU in this important field.</p><p> </p><p>My appointment is shared between the Department of Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy and the Department for Education. This role enables the two departments to maintain a coordinated approach across research and higher education.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>[1] A 2016 independent review by the Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council (EPSRC) found the UK fusion research programme to be ‘of world-class quality, in facilities, people and impact’.</p><p>[2] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/collaboration-on-science-and-innovation-a-future-partnership-paper" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/collaboration-on-science-and-innovation-a-future-partnership-paper</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-11-07T17:07:46.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782923/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782923/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782923/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Nuclear Fusion: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Education on the effect of the UK leaving the EU on nuclear fusion research in the UK.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","111260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782924","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-07","<p>The Valuation Office Agency (VOA) have received 83 complaints under their formal complaints procedure about the new business rates appeals system, Check, Challenge, Appeal (CCA), between 1 April 2017 and 31 October 2017.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-11-07T16:55:13.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782924/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782924/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782924/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-11-02","Non-domestic Rates: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many complaints he has received from businesses about the new system for contesting business rates since the revaluation of business rates in April 2017.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","111194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782926","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-09","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The UK artist’s resale right stems from the implementation of Directive 2001/84/EC on the resale right for the benefit of the author of an original work of art. The European Union (Withdrawal) Bill has powers to transpose directly-applicable EU law into UK law on exit, including the EU Directive on artist’s resale rights.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-11-09T14:22:12.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782926/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782926/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Art Works: Royalties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that the artist's resale right will continue to apply to artists and their heirs after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","111048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782927","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-10","<p>My officials and I have held extensive discussions with representatives from across the various IP sectors on the effects of the UK’s withdrawal from the EU, including the UK’s future relationship with the EU Intellectual Property Office. This future relationship is a matter for negotiation with the EU, and we will continue to explore all options.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is already an engaged and committed member of the World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO) in its own right, and will continue to fulfil its WIPO treaty obligations.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-11-10T14:08:32.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782927/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782927/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Intellectual Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with representatives from the Design, Trade Marks and Brands sectors on the future practical arrangements that will need to exist between the UK, the International Property Office and the EU Intellectual Property Office after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Ben Lake","Ceredigion","Ben Lake","111049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782928","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-07","<p>Information provided to the Government under Section 193 of the Trade Union and Labour Relations (Consolidation) Act 1992, regarding proposed redundancies is commercially confidential. The purpose of this information is to provide those facing redundancy, with assistance such as training and job seeking advice. Any information provided through this process is not in the public domain. It is open to employers to take legal action for breach of confidence if such unauthorised disclosures were made. Therefore, we are unable to provide the information requested.</p><p> </p><p>Officials at Defra have been in contact with Britvic. The company is in the process of consulting on the proposals with elected employee representatives and, therefore, it would be inappropriate for the Government to comment at this time. We know that this is an uncertain time for Britvic workers affected by the news and we will be working with the company to ensure that employees receive appropriate support.</p><p>Britvic is part of our dynamic and world-class food and drink industry, which is our largest manufacturing sector. It is a private company, and, therefore, the Government is not involved in its decision-making process. DWP stands ready to support the company’s workforce in the event of potential job losses.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","111067 ; 111068","2017-11-07T17:39:14.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782928/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782928/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-02","Britvic: Norwich","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he has received an HR1 form from Britvic Soft Drinks Ltd notifying him of the potential loss of jobs at the company's Norwich site.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","111066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782930","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-07","<p>Information provided to the Government under Section 193 of the Trade Union and Labour Relations (Consolidation) Act 1992, regarding proposed redundancies is commercially confidential. The purpose of this information is to provide those facing redundancy, with assistance such as training and job seeking advice. Any information provided through this process is not in the public domain. It is open to employers to take legal action for breach of confidence if such unauthorised disclosures were made. Therefore, we are unable to provide the information requested.</p><p> </p><p>Officials at Defra have been in contact with Britvic. The company is in the process of consulting on the proposals with elected employee representatives and, therefore, it would be inappropriate for the Government to comment at this time. We know that this is an uncertain time for Britvic workers affected by the news and we will be working with the company to ensure that employees receive appropriate support.</p><p>Britvic is part of our dynamic and world-class food and drink industry, which is our largest manufacturing sector. It is a private company, and, therefore, the Government is not involved in its decision-making process. DWP stands ready to support the company’s workforce in the event of potential job losses.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","111066 ; 111068","2017-11-07T17:39:14.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782930/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782930/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782930/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-02","Britvic: Norwich","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions he has made with the management at Britvic Soft Drinks Ltd on potential job losses in Norwich.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","111067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782931","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-11-07","<p>Information provided to the Government under Section 193 of the Trade Union and Labour Relations (Consolidation) Act 1992, regarding proposed redundancies is commercially confidential. The purpose of this information is to provide those facing redundancy, with assistance such as training and job seeking advice. Any information provided through this process is not in the public domain. It is open to employers to take legal action for breach of confidence if such unauthorised disclosures were made. Therefore, we are unable to provide the information requested.</p><p> </p><p>Officials at Defra have been in contact with Britvic. The company is in the process of consulting on the proposals with elected employee representatives and, therefore, it would be inappropriate for the Government to comment at this time. We know that this is an uncertain time for Britvic workers affected by the news and we will be working with the company to ensure that employees receive appropriate support.</p><p>Britvic is part of our dynamic and world-class food and drink industry, which is our largest manufacturing sector. It is a private company, and, therefore, the Government is not involved in its decision-making process. DWP stands ready to support the company’s workforce in the event of potential job losses.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","111066 ; 111067","2017-11-07T17:39:15.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782931/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782931/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782931/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-11-02","Britvic: Norwich","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with Britvic Soft Drinks Ltd on financial support for its site in Norwich.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","111068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782932","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-10","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p><p>The rollout of smart meters is on track to deliver significant benefits, including putting an end to estimated bills, and is set to save consumers £300m in 2020 alone. Suppliers are mandated by government to offer every household and small business a smart meter by 2020, and remain committed to this target.</p><p>Over 7.7 million smart meters are operating under the Programme.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-11-10T12:01:15.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782932/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782932/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782932/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the percentage of customers not taking up the offer of a smart meter from each of the major energy companies.","false","Biography information for John Grogan","Keighley","John Grogan","111081"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782933","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-10","<p>The only Departmental public phone line that charges members of the public to call is the Business Support Helpline (0300 456 3565).</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-11-10T12:00:11.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782933/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782933/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many and what proportion of his Department's public phone-lines charge members of the public to call.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","111097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782934","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-10","<p>The Department does not hold data on capital expenditure for individual offshore wind projects. The Department’s latest projection of capital expenditure for generic offshore wind projects is published in Arup (2016): Review of Renewable Electricity Generation Cost and Technical Assumptions, and can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/arup-2016-review-of-renewable-electricity-generation-cost-and-technical-assumptions" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/arup-2016-review-of-renewable-electricity-generation-cost-and-technical-assumptions</a>.</p><p>The Contracts for Difference (CfD) Second Allocation Round results, which were announced on 11 September 2017, showed one offshore wind project commissioning in 2021/22 cleared at a strike price of £74.75/MWh (2012 prices) and two offshore wind projects commissioning in year 2022/23 cleared at a strike price of £57.50/MWh (2012 prices). Both these prices represent a saving on the administrative strike price set using the data from Arup (2016), indicating that offshore wind costs are falling.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-11-10T12:02:03.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782934/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782934/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782934/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the offshore wind capital expenditure data was for each of the last two years; and what the evidential basis is for his Department's assessment of the fall in the cost of wind power.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","111098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782936","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-10","<ul><li>The first Contract For Difference (CfD) allocation round results, published in 2015, saw over 1.2 gigawatts of offshore wind capacity secure contracts, estimated at the time of the auction to cost consumers just over £240 million per year (2012 prices).</li><li>The second round results, announced in September 2017, saw the clearing price half for offshore wind delivered in the auction; we secured an additional 3.2 gigawatts of new offshore wind capacity, estimated at the time of the auction to cost consumers just over £130 million per year (2012 prices).</li><li>There are many factors that affect payments under these contracts, which mean that actual costs may go up or down.</li><li>These results demonstrate that the UK is an attractive place to invest, with a record amount of renewable capacity secured to power our homes.</li><li>The price of offshore wind clearing through the auction has halved in two years, demonstrating that competitive auctions are working well to drive down costs and deliver savings for consumers, whilst delivering the government’s decarbonisation ambitions.</li></ul>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-11-10T13:09:22.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782936/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782936/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782936/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Wind Power: Seas and Oceans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of guaranteeing the strike price to consumers of operational offshore wind sites in (a) 2015 and (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","111099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782938","Department for Education","false","2017-11-10","<p>There have been 43,600 apprenticeship starts for the provisional 2016/17 academic year since May 2017 to July 2017.</p><p>These figures are available in the Statistical First Release, published on 12 October 2017:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/650552/SFR_53_2017_main_tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/650552/SFR_53_2017_main_tables.ods</a>.</p><p>Additionally, the Further Education data library also holds further information and breakdowns for apprenticeship starts:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/fe-data-library" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/fe-data-library</a>.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-11-10T12:52:30.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782938/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782938/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782938/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-11-02","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the change has been in proportion and number of new apprenticeship starts since May 2017.","false","Biography information for Jared O'Mara","Sheffield, Hallam","Jared O'Mara","111001"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782939","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-07","<p>Ministers and officials have frequent discussions with their Treasury counterparts on a range of matters, including business rates.</p><p>My right hon. Friend the Chancellor of the Exchequer has set out the government’s position on this issue, most recently in his evidence to the Treasury Committee on 11 October.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-11-07T17:54:51.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782939/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782939/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782939/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Small Businesses: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on the effect of the staircase tax on small businesses.","false","Biography information for Toby Perkins","Chesterfield","Toby Perkins","110994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782940","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-10","<p>The Government and HMRC provide support and guidance to ensure employers in the social care sector understand and comply with National Minimum Wage law. The Government is also increasing funding going into the sector. In the spring Budget 2017, £2bn additional funding for local authorities was agreed for adult social care over the next three years. Funding agreed by Government since 2015 means councils have access in total to £9.25 billion more dedicated funding for social care over the next three years.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-11-10T09:43:56.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782940/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782940/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782940/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Social Services: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to ensure that people employed in the public sector social care sector receive the national living wage.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","111014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782941","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-11-10","<p>The United States Department of Commerce is investigating a complaint made by Boeing regarding the import of Bombardier’s C Series aircraft into the USA from Canada. Separately, the World Trade Organisation is examining the disputes between the European Union and the USA concerning Boeing and Airbus. These matters do not directly concern UK competition law.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-11-10T12:03:03.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782941/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782941/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782941/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-11-02","Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the implications for the future of UK competition law of the dispute between Bombardier, Airbus and Boeing; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","111035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782943","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-09","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) does not administer its own childcare facilities but supports parents to make their own arrangements through a combination of vouchers, allowances and participation in shared schemes, depending on where in the UK, and globally, employees work.</p><p>London based staff can make use of the Westminster Holiday Play Scheme organised by the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy. The Department does not have details on the number of individual staff members who use the scheme nor the overall cost; however we can confirm a cost of £35 per day/ per child of which the Department contributes £18.</p><p>UK Export Finance staff based at 1 Horse Guards Road can access the HM Treasury “holiday clubs” which are totally funded by the employee.</p><p>For DIT overseas staff, local arrangements are available within their overseas allowances.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-11-09T11:59:09.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782943/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782943/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782943/answer","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782943/answer/previousversion/21271","Biography information for Greg Hands","202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-11-02","Department for International Trade: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what childcare facilities his Department makes available for its staff; how much his Department spent (a) overall and (b) per child on those facilities in the last 12 months; and how many of his Department's staff use those facilities.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","111065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782944","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-13","<p>Following the referendum in June 2016, the Department for International Trade (DIT) continues to make rigorous preparations for a range of possible outcomes from the UK's negotiations with the EU. This is the job of a responsible government.</p><p>This preparation includes consideration of possible alternatives to a negotiated agreement, to ensure continued prosperity for business, workers and consumers across the UK.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-11-13T17:17:07.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782944/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782944/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782944/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-11-02","Department for International Trade: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of his Department's preparations for the UK leaving the EU with (a) an agreement on future partnership and (b) no agreement with the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","111214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782945","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-10","<p>Legal services are a key export for the UK, with the UK legal services sector the most international legal sector in the world. We expect access to the UK’s legal services sector to continue to be in high demand.</p><p>The Department for International Trade is engaged with the Ministry of Justice, other Departments and representatives of the legal services sector to discuss opportunities to further promote the UK legal services sector, and the benefits of the UK legal systems, overseas. The Rt Hon Lord Keen of Elie QC launched the ‘Legal Services are GREAT’ campaign in October.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-11-10T14:27:11.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782945/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782945/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782945/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-11-02","Legal Profession: Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of future trends in exports by the UK legal services sector.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","111146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782946","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-13","<p>Many non-UK firms recognise the excellent business environment in the UK, and choose to invest and operate here. The UK is a very attractive destination for all foreign investment, with open markets, a long-term track record on the rule of law, a transparent regulatory system, a simple and competitive tax system and a highly skilled labour force – and the World Bank rates us 7<sup>th</sup> for ease of doing business.</p><p>As global champions of free and fair trade, we want to ensure that companies have the maximum freedom to trade and operate within European markets.</p><p>The UK Government is committed to securing a deep and special partnership with the EU, including a bold and ambitious Free Trade Agreement.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","111148 ; 111149 ; 111150","2017-11-13T17:30:49.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782946/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782946/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/782946/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-11-02","Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what assessment he has made of the importance to international trade of the UK's current position as a point of entry to the EU single market.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","111147"
